la de Fife42岁。他和Maria Bisset至少有1个儿子。他去世于大约1249年在英国苏格兰阿爾迪史爾享年51岁。"},"hr":{"about 1200–about 1249":"oko 1200.–oko 1249.","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–preminula","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–preminuo","1160–Female":"1160–preminula","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"oko 1249.","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"oko 1200.","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"oko 1230.","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Škotska, United Kingdom","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Škotska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"about 1200–about 1249":"okolo 1200–okolo 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Zesnulá","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Zesnulý","1160–Female":"1160–Zesnulá","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"okolo 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"okolo 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"okolo 1230","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1200–about 1249":"omkring 1200–omkring 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Afdød","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Afdød","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"omkring 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"omkring 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"omkring 1230","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1200–about 1249":"circa 1200–circa 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Overleden","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Overleden","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"circa 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"circa 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"circa 1230","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1200–about 1249":"about 1200–about 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Deceased","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"about 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"about 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"about 1230","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish, English, and especially Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graney","meanings":["Irish (Galway, Cork, and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Raighne</b> ‘son of <i>Raighne</i>’, a pet form of <i>Raghnall</i>. It has sometimes been changed to   Grant  . See also   Rainey  .","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Gräni</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Grand","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."]},{"name":"Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."]},{"name":"General","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word <i>general</i>, possibly adopted as a surname in honor of a certain general of the US army, most probably Ulysses S. Grant (see   Grant  , compare   President  ). Compare also 3 below.","German: nickname for a mercenary (employed in royal services).","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): nickname from Spanish <i>general</i> ‘general’ (military officer)."]}]},{"name":"Gregory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Grant","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, common in Scotland, where it is the name of a famous clan. It is derived from a nickname meaning ‘large’ (Anglo-Norman <i>grand</i>). In the United States the name is sometimes bestowed in honour of the Civil War general and 18th president,  Ulysses S. Grant  (  1822–85 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gregory - Le Grant Grant 1st of Stratherrick was born about 1200, in Inverness-shire, Scotland, his father, Amhlaim \"Auley\" Grant, was 52 and his mother, Darvagilla de Fife, was 42. He had at least 1 son with Maria Bisset. He died about 1249, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1200–about 1249":"umbes 1200–umbes 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Surnud","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"umbes 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Inverugie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1200–about 1249":"noin 1200–noin 1249","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1201–Female":"1201–Kuollut","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1249":"1249","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","about 1249":"noin 1249","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","about 1200":"noin 1200","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","ab